# Stack Implementation Using Linked List in C++

This document explains how to implement a **Stack Data Structure** using a **Singly Linked List** in C++.

Unlike array-based stacks, this implementation **does not suffer from fixed size limitations** and supports **dynamic memory allocation**.

---

## ðŸ“Œ Stack Principle

- **LIFO** â€“ Last In, First Out
- All operations happen at the **top** of the stack
- The top of the stack is represented by the **head node** of the linked list

---

## ðŸ“¥ Input

- User-defined stack operations (push, pop, peek)

---

## ðŸ“¤ Output

- Stack elements
- Top element
- Error messages for underflow conditions

---

## ðŸ§  Stack Operations

| Operation | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `push(x)` | Insert element at the top of the stack |
| `pop()` | Remove and return the top element |
| `peek()` | View the top element |
| `isEmpty()` | Check whether the stack is empty |
| `display()` | Display all elements in the stack |

---

## ðŸ’» C++ Implementation (Linked List)

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class Node {
public:
    int data;
    Node* next;

    Node(int x) {
        data = x;
        next = nullptr;
    }
};

class Stack {
private:
    Node* top;

public:
    Stack() {
        top = nullptr;
    }

    // Push operation
    void push(int x) {
        Node* newNode = new Node(x);
        newNode->next = top;
        top = newNode;
    }

    // Pop operation
    int pop() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Stack underflow" << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        Node* temp = top;
        int poppedValue = temp->data;
        top = top->next;
        delete temp;
        return poppedValue;
    }

    // Peek operation
    int peek() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Stack is empty" << endl;
            return -1;
        }
        return top->data;
    }

    // Check if stack is empty
    bool isEmpty() {
        return top == nullptr;
    }

    // Display stack elements
    void display() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            cout << "Stack is empty" << endl;
            return;
        }
        Node* curr = top;
        while (curr != nullptr) {
            cout << curr->data << " ";
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Stack s;

    s.push(10);
    s.push(20);
    s.push(30);

    s.display();

    s.pop();
    s.display();

    cout << "Top element: " << s.peek() << endl;

    return 0;
}

Time Complexity
| Operation | Complexity |
| --------- | ---------- |
| Push      | O(1)       |
| Pop       | O(1)       |
| Peek      | O(1)       |
| Display   | O(n)       |


Space Complexity

| Feature        | Array Stack | Linked List Stack      |
| -------------- | ----------- | ---------------------- |
| Size           | Fixed       | Dynamic                |
| Overflow       | Yes         | No (until memory full) |
| Memory         | Contiguous  | Non-contiguous         |
| Implementation | Simple      | Slightly complex       |

ðŸ“Œ Key Takeaways

Linked list stack avoids size limitations

Push and pop are always O(1)

Preferred when stack size is unpredictable
